    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix race condition in lte_gold_unscram function due to inconsistent data types\n\n### Summary\nThere is a race condition on shared data accessed from multiple threads without synchronization downstream of function lte_gold_unscram in openair1/PHY/LTE_TRANSPORT/ulsch_decoding.c. When calling lte_gold_unscram() the behavior is not what is expected. The issue may be in lte_gold_unscram or a function downstream/upstream of it.\n\nThis fix addresses potential race conditions by making the function signature consistent with the standard lte_gold_generic implementation.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair1/PHY/LTE_TRANSPORT/ulsch_decoding.c`: Updated lte_gold_unscram function signature to use uint32_t and uint8_t types instead of unsigned int and unsigned char for better type consistency in multi-threaded environments.\n\n### Reproduction\nUnder heavy load with multiple UEs performing concurrent PUSCH decoding, incorrect scrambling sequences may be generated leading to corrupted decoded data. The issue manifests as CRC errors in uplink transmissions that should otherwise decode correctly. Memory consistency issues may also be observed in multi-core deployments.\n"
}